<font color="#FF0000">A THOUGHT OR TWO!</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13  0:24:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Nam vets,<br>
What happened  to this country during the period of 1965 to 1973?  As a person, one generation removed, the son of a Nam vet, I am still seeking that answer.  How could this country go from patriotism, God, and apple pie, to a country that turned its back on the young men it sent to war?  I read a article recently, that young men were sitting in VA hospitals in the early 1970's waiting up to three years for a artificial limb.  I just can't understand that!  Not when the US Air Force was spending millions on a single mission (risking the lives of pilots) to bomb a suspected truck park in the red river delta, some target choosen only for political considerations as not offend the North Vietnamese.<br>
I don't think anyone who was not a part of the war or affected by it can ever fully understand.  I've been trying since I was 12.  I understand the aftermath, since I've seen that with my own two eyes, but not the American mentality that can send American boys to a asian country to fight a confused war, then turned its back on them when they came home like they were some horrible, misbehaving child whose place in polite American society was questionable.  The Vietnam legacy is the most conflicting and confusing in our history.<br><br>
Many people in this country are guilty, not of any other crime other then ignorance, apathy, and their turning their backs on you vets.<br>
The Vietnam vet came home over a period of years, did not organize like the World War II to gain political recognition and power.  Instead the vets tried to find an American that was not there anymore, a America that didn't want to hear about the war.<br><br>
There is a legacy and a answer to this.  I ask this as a trained educator, don't let your experiences be lost or hidden.  The youth of American need to hear about the pain, the loss, the death not only of Vietnamese, but of young Americans that had futures cut short.  SW is right, don't be silent, no one has the RIGHT to silence you.  If they would not listen then, then they have to listen now.  Share that part of your lives, in hopes that the new kids of America will have just a speck of the insight and pain that is carried by those who fight for America.  Maybe, just maybe this will be enough to save some American lives in the future, to keep the richest, most secure country in the world from ignoring the warrior or the reasons for war ever again.  Children need to understand, too hear.  We can't avoid a history because we feel its violence is politically incorrect. As vets, locate each other, embrace your brothers, pick each other up and stand together.  Its time that Vietnam vets make there voice heard here in America.  If you don't want to do it for you, do it for those victims of war that no longer have a voice.  America needs (and I thinks some of them want) to understand.  The human legacy of war is what counts now.  We can argue about Agent Orange, the bombing campaign, the failures of heavy firepower, the question of the legitimacy of the war, we can argue them forever with no satisfactory answer, and for what we can't change the past, only hopefully learn and grow from it.<br><br>
America needs to hear the human legacy, the feelings, the tears, the joys, the smallest details.  What seems insignificant to you could tell someone more than a textbook could ever.  As a teacher, for many lessons I write objectives that not only deal with knowledge and the learning process (cognitive), but affective objectives, those deal with feelings, emotions.  Its your human legacy that is part of America.  I often sit back and wonder, how much of the Vietnam legacy is still here with us in America.  With a little investigation, much of it is still here.  Native American tribes understood the &quot;warrior&quot; and what he went through.  They understood and RESPECTED his insight into life and death, his understanding of crisis and emotion.  Hopefully America will some day see the wisdom in this insighful Native American observation.<br><br>
Navy Lieutenant Richard Strandberg wrote home to his wife susan from Vietnam in 1968 and said, &quot;Maybe this war will end soon. Wishful thinking?  Yes, the Vietnam War will never end.&quot;  He was right the war can't never end.  The peace is more hurtful than the war.<br><br>
Well, hope I didn't get too philosophical!  Peace!  Keep your ammo dry and don't fall asleep on perimeter!
<p><code>-- --  (Joe DeLeva) </code><p>


